### has_many :through (Many-to-Many)

Association through a join model.

```ruby
# app/models/article.rb
class Article < ApplicationRecord
  has_many :article_tags
  has_many :tags, through: :article_tags
end

# app/models/article_tag.rb (join model)
class ArticleTag < ApplicationRecord
  belongs_to :article
  belongs_to :tag
end

# app/models/tag.rb
class Tag < ApplicationRecord
  has_many :article_tags
  has_many :articles, through: :article_tags
end
```

**Database Structure:**
```ruby
# articles table
- id
- title

# tags table
- id
- name

# article_tags table (join table)
- id
- article_id
- tag_id
- created_at (optional: track when tagged)
```

**Usage:**
```ruby
article = Article.first
article.tags              # Returns array of Tags
article.tags << tag       # Add tag to article
article.tags.delete(tag)  # Remove tag from article
article.tags = [tag1, tag2]  # Replace all tags

tag = Tag.first
tag.articles              # Returns array of Articles
```

**has_many :through Options:**
```ruby
class Article < ApplicationRecord
  has_many :article_tags, dependent: :destroy
  has_many :tags, through: :article_tags
  
  # Source (if name doesn't match)
  has_many :article_categorizations
  has_many :categories, through: :article_categorizations, source: :category
  
  # Scope through association
  has_many :recent_comments, 
           -> { where('created_at > ?', 1.week.ago) },
           through: :articles,
           source: :comments
end
```

